                From the Survey: Lazard Ltd.


                    Daniel Henigson
                
 | November 26, 2014
                
                






 Founded in 1848, Lazard Ltd. (LAZ) operates as a financial advisory and asset management company. The asset manager engages in investment banking, provides investment advisory products and services, and manages more than $180 billion in assets across the globe. Lazard’s traditional and alternative investment services cover listed equity and fixed-income securities for a broad range of clients, including both institutional and retail services. Moreover the company, which is based in New York City, has a number of subsidiaries that help it operate in 41 cities across 26 countries in North America, Europe, Asia, Australia, and South America.
Lazard is engaged in two primary businesses; Financial Advisory and Asset Management. The company’s revenue, which is split just about equally between the two, eclipsed $2 billion for the first time in 2013. The organization has been flourishing of late, as favorable fundamentals have enabled the shares to retain a good portion of their 12-month gains even as the market has undergone some painful selling. Lazard was able to increase its assets under management (AUM) by 15% in 2013, and will likely see another 10%-15% boost by this year’s end. Moreover, we think that Lazard’s diversification and strong asset allocation strategies will help it weather eventual rate hikes by the Federal Reserve. For the time being, however, we see near zero interest-rate policies (ZIRP) acting as a boost to Lazard’s overall equity strategy, auguring well for the near term.
BusinessStrategy
Management continues to focus on strengthening its marketing and consulting capabilities. In doing so, the company concentrates on expanding its geographic footprint and leveraging its vast amount of resources to gain new business relationships and increase ongoing ones. Over the past several years, the strategic plan that the company has implemented involved hiring more senior investment professionals and portfolio managers, enhancing investment performance, expanding the product platform, and improving business results in areas where it has struggled.
The Economic Backdrop
Economic and global financial conditions are the keys to what drives Lazard’s success. Recently, the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics reported (a revised) 3.9% GDP growth for the third quarter. Payroll reports have also shown underlying strength in the economy, as has manufacturing. Indeed, we see the economy further improving and suspect that 2015 will add momentum to the recovery. Unfortunately, things across the globe are deteriorating. More specifically, the European economy seems closer to contracting than expanding. Just recently, the European Central Bank elected to enact policies similar to the Federal Reserve’s bond-buying program known as Quantitative Easing. If the new measures are adequate and serve to improve the economy, that could give Lazard a boost in its European business, which comprises about a third of its overall revenue.
Competitors
Lazard continues to grow at an impressive rate despite competing with several different corporations of much larger stature. Some of these include industry leader BlackRock, Inc. (BLK), T. Rowe Price (TROW), and Franklin Resources (BEN). Although Lazard operates in a diverse, competitive, and fast-rising industry, we believe the company is well suited to deal with the many challenges that lie ahead. In fact, Lazard has been one of the top performing stocks in the financial services industry throughout 2014, and we see that as a sign of continuing investor confidence and strong business results.
Conclusion
All told, we think investors should take a hard look at Lazard Ltd. The company’s strengths can be seen in its Asset Management business, where it has become one of the leaders in that industry and in its strong financial advisory business. Moreover, we believe that Lazard has the ability to leverage its existing infrastructure and wide ranging network to capitalize on the global macroeconomic recovery that could play out in 2015. Subscribers interested in learning more about this financial services company are advised to consult Value Line’s quarterly reports for Lazard, as well as any supplemental issuances and relevant articles that may arise as important news comes to light.
At the time of this article’s writing, the author did not have positions in any of the companies mentioned.









